---
import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "~/components/Breadcrumbs.astro";

const updated = "2026-06-16";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy policy"
  description="What this site collects, what it sends, and what it stores. The short answer: almost nothing."
  ogImage="/og/privacy.png"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-10">
    <Breadcrumbs
      crumbs={[{ label: "Home", href: "/" }, { label: "Privacy" }]}
    />
    <article class="prose-spec mt-6">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink-900">
        Privacy policy
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-500">Last updated {updated}</p>

      <p>
        This site is a static, publicly readable reference. There are no user
        accounts, no comments, no forms, and no transactions. We collect a small
        amount of aggregate analytics — see below — and nothing else. This page
        exists because the spec lists a privacy policy as <strong
          >required</strong
        >, and because honest disclosure is the only kind worth publishing.
      </p>

      <h2 id="data-controller">Data controller</h2>
      <p>
        Joost de Valk (<a href="https://joost.blog" rel="external">joost.blog</a
        >) operates this site as a personal open-source project. For privacy
        questions, email <a href="mailto:privacy@specification.website"
          >privacy@specification.website</a
        >.
      </p>

      <h2 id="what-we-collect">What we collect</h2>
      <p>
        The site sets <strong>no cookies</strong> and stores nothing in your browser.
        For ordinary browser visits, the only data we collect is aggregate page-view
        analytics via
        <a href="https://plausible.io" rel="external">Plausible</a> (separate server-side
        aggregate logging for crawlers and MCP / A2A calls is described under <a
          href="#logs-and-hosting">Logs and hosting</a
        >):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>URL of the page you loaded.</li>
        <li>HTTP referrer (which site sent you, if any).</li>
        <li>
          Browser, operating system, and device type — derived from the
          User-Agent string and discarded after the request.
        </li>
        <li>
          Country, derived from your IP address. <strong
            >Your IP address itself is never stored.</strong
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In two situations we also send Plausible a named <a
          href="https://plausible.io/docs/custom-event-goals"
          rel="external">custom event</a
        > (to the same <code>plausible.io</code> endpoint, still with no cookies and
        no identifier):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Missing pages.</strong> When you reach a page that does not exist,
          we send a <code>404</code> event with the path you tried to load, so we
          can find and fix broken links.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Site search.</strong> When you use the search page or the ⌘K overlay,
          we send a <code>Search</code> event with <strong
            >the text you typed</strong
          >, how many results it returned, and whether anything matched. This
          shows us what people look for and which topics are missing. The query
          is sent as aggregate event data — it is not joined to your IP, a
          cookie, or any identifier, and nothing is stored in your browser. If
          you would rather not send your search text, block <code
            >plausible.io</code
          > (see below) or browse without searching.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>What Plausible deliberately does not do:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No cookies, no localStorage, no fingerprinting.</li>
        <li>
          No cross-site tracking. No identifier follows you to another site.
        </li>
        <li>
          No personal data, no profiles, no advertising. The data is aggregated
          and cannot be used to identify you.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Plausible is GDPR, CCPA, and PECR compliant by design and does not
        require a cookie banner. See <a
          href="https://plausible.io/data-policy"
          rel="external">Plausible's data policy</a
        > and
        <a href="https://plausible.io/privacy" rel="external">privacy policy</a> for
        the full detail. Aggregate statistics are stored on EU servers operated by
        Plausible Insights OÜ in Estonia.
      </p>
      <p>Beyond analytics:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No accounts, no login, no profile data.</li>
        <li>No forms — there is nothing to submit.</li>
        <li>
          No third-party scripts other than the single Plausible request to <code
            >plausible.io/js/script.js</code
          >.
        </li>
        <li>No advertising network.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="logs-and-hosting">Logs and hosting</h2>
      <p>
        The site is hosted on <a
          href="https://pages.cloudflare.com/"
          rel="external">Cloudflare Pages</a
        >. Cloudflare may process request metadata (IP address, user-agent,
        requested URL, timestamp) as a normal part of serving the site and
        protecting it from abuse, governed by Cloudflare's own
        <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/privacypolicy/" rel="external"
          >privacy policy</a
        >. We do not receive a copy of that data and do not use it for
        analytics.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do record aggregate request metadata for three request streams in
        <a
          href="https://developers.cloudflare.com/analytics/analytics-engine/"
          rel="external">Cloudflare Analytics Engine</a
        >
        — an internal dashboard at <code>/admin/stats</code> (gated by Cloudflare
        Access) reads it:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Crawler / AI-agent traffic:</strong> when a request matches a known
          AI / LLM / search crawler User-Agent, carries a <code
            >Signature-Agent</code
          > header, is verified-bot per Cloudflare, or asks for <code
            >text/markdown</code
          >, we record the bot name, path, country, method, referer, and
          User-Agent (truncated). No IP address is stored.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>MCP / A2A calls</strong> to <code
            >mcp.specification.website</code
          >: we record the JSON-RPC method, tool name, the first 500 bytes of
          arguments, client name/version, protocol version, country, and
          User-Agent (truncated). No IP address is stored.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Browser policy reports:</strong> the site uses the <a
            href="/spec/security/reporting-endpoints/">Reporting API</a
          >, so your browser may POST a structured report when a page violates a
          security policy (for example a Content Security Policy block) or uses
          a deprecated browser feature. We record the report type, the path it
          occurred on, the directive or feature involved, and the User-Agent
          (truncated). This fires only on a policy violation — never on an
          ordinary page view — and carries no cookie, no identifier, and no IP
          address.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of these streams tracks your browsing: the first two are non-human
        traffic, and the third fires only when a policy is violated. They are
        kept to understand which agents use the spec and the MCP server, and to
        catch security-policy and deprecation regressions. The data lives in
        Cloudflare's Analytics Engine under our account; retention follows
        Cloudflare's defaults.
      </p>

      <h2 id="content-hosting">GitHub</h2>
      <p>
        Source content lives on <a
          href="https://github.com/jdevalk/specification.website"
          rel="external">GitHub</a
        >. If you open an issue or pull request, that interaction is governed by
        <a
          href="https://docs.github.com/en/site-policy/privacy-policies/github-general-privacy-statement"
          rel="external">GitHub's privacy statement</a
        >, not this one.
      </p>

      <h2 id="signals-we-respect">Signals we respect</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong
            >Do Not Track / <a href="/spec/privacy/global-privacy-control/"
              >Global Privacy Control</a
            >:</strong
          > Plausible does not respect DNT or GPC because the analytics it runs do
          not constitute the kind of tracking those signals were designed to stop.
          If you disagree, block <code>plausible.io</code> in your browser or use
          an extension such as uBlock Origin — the site continues to work without
          it.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Browser content blockers:</strong> the Plausible request is blocked
          by all common content blockers. We notice no difference; you get the same
          site.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="children">Children</h2>
      <p>
        The site is a public technical reference. It is suitable for anyone,
        including under-13s, because it collects no personal data and has no
        interactive features.
      </p>

      <h2 id="changes">Changes to this policy</h2>
      <p>
        If the site ever changes in a way that adds data collection (it should
        not), we will update the date at the top of this page and announce the
        change in the
        <a
          href="https://github.com/jdevalk/specification.website"
          rel="external">repository</a
        >.
      </p>

      <h2 id="your-rights">Your rights</h2>
      <p>
        Under the UK GDPR and EU GDPR you have the right to access, correct,
        delete, restrict, and port any personal data we hold on you. Because we
        hold none, the practical answer to any such request is “we have nothing
        on you”. If you believe we are mistaken, email us and we will
        investigate within 30 days.
      </p>

      <h2 id="related">Related</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="/spec/privacy/privacy-policy/"
            >The spec page on privacy policies</a
          > — what this page is required to cover, and why.
        </li>
        <li><a href="/spec/privacy/">All privacy-category spec pages</a>.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
